| rev7 = [[Sputnikmusic]]
| rev7score = 4.1/5<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fisher|first1=Greg|title=Mastodon Once More 'Round the Sun|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/62917/Mastodon-Once-More-Round-the-Sun/|website=Sputnikmusic|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>
}}

''Once More 'Round the Sun'' was well received by contemporary [[music journalism|music critics]] upon its initial release. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from [[music critic]]s, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 78, which indicates "generally favorable reviews", based on 28 reviews.<ref name=metacritic/>

In the review for [[AllMusic]], writer Thom Jurek wrote that "Once More 'Round the Sun furthers what Mastodon began on [[The Hunter (Mastodon album)|The Hunter]]: expanding their music past metal's rigid borders -- toward an integrative sound that doesn't leave metal out."<ref name=allmusic/> Michael Madden also praised the album in the review for ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'', claiming that "Mastodon are starting to look more like that band’s peers, not disciples. Nick Raskulinecz’s eternally crunchy production helps them reach those heights on Once More ‘Round the Sun, and, as Oakland artist Skinner’s cover suggests, the record is vibrant, too. There could be more structural risk-taking and the band could stand to have more grandiose moments, but, well, you know: Consider them six for six."<ref name=CoS/> Dom Lawson spoke highly of the album in his review for ''[[The Guardian]]'' writing that "Once More 'Round the Sun sounds very much like the album they need to make to edge a little further into the mainstream – it has a largely straightforward air and a tendency to favour the big hooks of 2011's The Hunter over the labyrinthine weirdness of 2009's [[Crack the Skye]]."<ref name=guardian/>

Giving the album and eight out on ten for ''[[PopMatters]]'', Dean Brown felt that "when compared to the band’s previous stratospheric evolutions, its substance may be just as important to the tale of Mastodon when the inevitable is written, hopefully decades into the future and many albums later from one of the best bands, regardless of genre, roaming the earth at present."<ref name=popmatters/> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' writer Johnathan Zwickel shared similar sentiments, claiming that "While the rest of heavy music’s luminaries follow in their wake, Mastodon’s sound — and their ambition — is bigger than metal."<ref name=spin/>

Zoe Camp was more critical of the album in the review for ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', stating "it's possible to view Once More 'Round the Sun as a vow to honor their roots, even as they set out in search of broader horizons. So far, however, Mastodon’s paradigms simply don’t mesh the way they should. Evolution takes time, and Mastodon continue to publicly work out their growing pains as they determine which traits best represent the unified sound they’ve been chasing this decade."

===Accolades===
The album appeared on several album of the year lists published in 2014. ''[[Kerrang!]]'' ranked it as it's 28th best album of the year, it appeared on ''[[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]]'' magazine's end-of year list at #29 and on ''[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]]'' magazine's list at #35.<ref name="EoY">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A5464.htm|title=Acclaimed Music - One More 'Round the Sun|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Loudwire]]'' list the album as number 5 on their list of the 20 Best Metal Albums of 2014<ref name="LoudwireAlbum">{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/best-metal-albums-2014/|title=20 Best Metal Albums of 2014|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> and the song "Chimes at Midnight" at number 3 on their list of the 20 Best Metal Songs of 2014.<ref name="LoudwireSong">{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/best-metal-songs-of-2014/|title=20 Best Metal Songs of 2014|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref>

